You are my senior software architect and implementation engineer.

I am building a lightweight mobile-to-desktop control system.
This is NOT a full remote desktop app.
Do NOT implement live screen streaming.

Project goal:
Build a lightweight command-based remote control system where a mobile app can control a desktop over LAN. The system should support desktop controls, browser/site automation, screenshots on demand, and saved workflows/macros.

Core constraints:
- No live screen sharing
- LAN-first MVP
- Lightweight architecture
- Clean modular codebase
- Production-style folder structure
- No unnecessary dependencies
- Build phase by phase, not all at once
- Every phase must be runnable before moving on

Primary stack:
- Mobile app: Flutter
- Desktop app: Tauri + Rust
- Communication: Socket-based real-time command messaging over LAN
- Browser automation: Playwright
- Local persistence: SQLite
- Shared command/event contract: JSON-based schema

Monorepo structure:
remote-control-project/
├── mobile_app/
├── desktop_agent/
├── shared_schema/
├── docs/
├── scripts/
├── README.md

Architecture:
- Mobile app sends commands
- Desktop agent receives commands
- Desktop agent routes commands to handlers
- Desktop agent returns status/result/error
- Screenshot requests return image responses
- Browser automation is separate from native system controls
- Workflow/macro engine should be separate from both

Core feature groups:
1. Native desktop control
   - lock system
   - shutdown/restart/sleep
   - volume controls
   - open/close apps
   - keyboard typing
   - hotkeys
   - mouse clicks/scroll
   - screenshot on demand

2. Browser automation
   - open URL
   - search Google
   - search YouTube
   - search GitHub
   - refresh tab
   - close tab

3. Workflow engine
   - saved macros
   - action chains
   - favorites
   - reusable command presets

Code quality rules:
- Use clean modular architecture
- Keep code readable and maintainable
- Separate UI, transport, handlers, and domain logic
- Use strongly typed models where possible
- No giant files
- No duplicated logic
- Add TODO markers only for real future work
- Do not fake completion
- If something is incomplete, explicitly mark it

Output rules:
- First, explain the implementation plan for the requested phase
- Then generate the folder/file structure for that phase
- Then generate the code
- Then explain how to run it
- Then list known limitations
- Then suggest the next phase

Important:
Only implement the requested phase.
Do not jump ahead unless asked.